    <!-- =============================================
     SLIDE 9 - FUTURE WORK
     Per Alex: "each arm" → "every actor".
     Consistent actor terminology throughout.
     ============================================= -->
    <section class="slide">
      <header class="chrome">
        <span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span
        ><span class="dot g"></span>
        <span class="path">~/Inter-Act/09-future</span>
        <span class="branch"></span>
      </header>

      <div class="slide-content">
        <p class="eyebrow reveal">Future work</p>
        <h2 class="section-title reveal">
          Where INTER<span style="color: var(--green)">.</span>act is heading
        </h2>

        <p class="reveal muted" style="max-width: 78ch">
          Three tracks on our radar. The first is the headline - it's how the
          right-side diagram becomes real.
        </p>

        <div
          class="roadmap reveal"
          style="grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr)"
        >
          <div class="milestone dream">
            <div class="when">▸ AI · brain-to-brain</div>
            <h3>Peer to peer messaging/coordination</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>
                The shared message bus from the architecture diagram becomes
                real - actors negotiate handovers directly, <strong>no
                backend in the loop</strong>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Each actor advertises what it can reach and offer; chains
                self-assemble through peer requests, no central authority
                assigning roles.
              </li>
              <li>
                Linear pipeline first, peer bidding next - then we drop the
                temporary backend.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="milestone next">
            <div class="when">▸ UI · click &amp; create</div>
            <h3>Node-RED-style builder</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Drag-and-drop</strong> actors, so nobody has to
                hand-edit YAML or code.
              </li>
              <li>Parallel routes instead of one linear chain.</li>
              <li>
                Set each actor's speed, capacity, and max load right in the UI.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="milestone next">
            <div class="when">▸ Honesty · where it breaks</div>
            <h3>Limitations &amp; fallback</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Per-actor fallback</strong>: what each actor does
                when its brain can't decide, when the bus drops messages,
                when a peer goes silent.
              </li>
              <li>
                Negative tests: routing deadlocks, failed handovers, brain
                stalls - actor degrades to its scripted path.
              </li>
              <li>
                Defined in a behaviour file, same shape for every actor type.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="slide-number">09<span class="of"> / 10</span></div>
    </section>

